article.description: Courtney Paris had 25 points and 16 rebounds for her 122nd career double-double as Oklahoma clinched a share of the Big 12 title with a 73-63 win over Oklahoma State.
article.headline: Oklahoma tops Oklahoma St. for share of sixth Big 12 title
article.linkText: No. 3 Oklahoma clinches share of Big 12 crown
article.story:
NORMAN, Okla. -- Bedlam seems to bring out the best in Jenny Vining.

The sophomore guard, pressed into extended action because of injuries and foul trouble, hit five 3-pointers and scored a season-high 15 points for Oklahoma (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP)
 on Saturday as the Sooners clinched a share of their sixth Big 12 Conference title with a 73-63 win over Oklahoma State.

Senior center Courtney Paris was her usual dominant self, finishing with 25 points and 16 rebounds for her 122nd career double-double as Oklahoma (25-3, 13-1) bounced back from a one-point midweek loss at No. 12 Texas A&M that ended the Sooners' 20-game winning streak.

But it was Vining and two other guards who usually play reserve roles -- sophomore Nyeshia Stevenson and freshman Jasmine Hartman -- who provided the spark for the Sooners as they rallied from a six-point first half deficit against Oklahoma State (15-12, 4-10).

"We've been talking all year about the importance of depth, particularly when it gets to postseason play, the conference tournament and the NCAA tournament," Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale said. "Your depth is critical and we felt like that's a weapon that we maybe haven't had in the past."

Andrea Riley scored 29 points to lead Oklahoma State, which suffered a serious blow to any hopes of receiving an at-large bid to the NCAA tournament. The Cowgirls have lost 20 of the last 21 games in the Bedlam series against the Sooners, including 11 straight in Norman. Overall, Oklahoma State has dropped seven of its last eight.

"I thought we stuck to the game plan and gave ourselves a chance," Oklahoma State coach Kurt Budke said. "We lost a little momentum before halftime and that was tough to get back. ... There is no quit in this team. I think you saw that today."

Oklahoma played its second game without starting shooting guard Whitney Hand, who suffered a broken left index finger on Feb. 21 in a win over Baylor. Stevenson replaced her in the starting lineup.

Then, 38 seconds into the second half, starting point guard Danielle Robinson picked up her fourth foul. Hartman, her backup, teamed so well running the point with Stevenson that Robinson never needed to come back into the game. Robinson had two points in a season-low 13 minutes while Hartman played a career-high 27 minutes, finishing with two points and four turnovers.

Against Texas A&M, the Sooners committed a season-high 29 turnovers but had only 11 against Oklahoma State.

Vining scored in double figures for only the third time this season. Her previous season high of 12 points came against Oklahoma State in Stillwater.

"I didn't think about that until after the game," she said. "I came out and did what I'm supposed to do. I'm a shooter."

Coale raved about the play of her guards.

"That experience, you can't put a price tag on it," she said. "It's not about, 'Are they 10 times a better player than they were a week ago?' No. But you get those minutes under your belt and then you're able to show what you can do."

Unlike the first Bedlam game, in which the Sooners built an 18-point lead in the first 11 minutes and never trailed en route to a 93-75 win, the Cowgirls pushed Oklahoma early. Oklahoma State did so by controlling the boards and slowing the pace for much of the first half while going 4-of-8 from 3-point range.

The Cowgirls took their first lead at 17-15 on a 3-pointer by Taylor Hardeman with 12:54 left in the first half. Oklahoma played from behind until Vining's 3-pointer from the corner in the final minute of the half put the Sooners ahead 33-31 at halftime.

"The first 20 [minutes] was very good," Budke said. "But this isn't just some average team we're playing out there. It was one of the two best teams in the country."

The Sooners opened the second half on a 12-2 run to open up a 45-33 lead. Stevenson scored 10 of her 13 points during that stretch, on two 3-pointers and four free throws.

Oklahoma State came no closer than 10 points the rest of the way as the Sooners built their lead to as many as 24 points, 62-38 on a 3-pointer by Vining with 11:19 left.

"I felt like the first four minutes of the second half would tell the tale, and they did," Coale said.

Amanda Thompson punctuated the win for Oklahoma, racing to block a layup attempt by Riley from behind with 3:58 left. Thompson blocked four shots for the Sooners.

A 12-3 game-ending run by Oklahoma State cut the final margin to 10 points. Shaunte Smith had 15 points and 12 rebounds to record her sixth double-double of the season for the Cowgirls, who were outrebounded 45-33 by Oklahoma.
